{{more citations needed|date=January 2018}}
The denuded area of skin seen around projectile wounds is called an '''abrasion collar'''. Though this findings is often seen around [[rifle]]d firearm entry wounds, some other high speed projectile wounds can also have this finding.<ref name="Ajay">{{cite journal|last1=Gujaral|first1=PB|last2=Ajay|first2=B|title=Abrasion Collar Around Shrapnel Entry Wound.|journal=J Forensic Sci|date=28 February 2017|doi=10.1111/1556-4029.13457|pmid=28244192|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=abrasion+collar+around+shrapnel+entry+wound|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref> A similar finding is also likely in firearm [[exit wound]]s if the skin at the exit was crushed between the outgoing [[bullet]] and an unyielding object pressed against the skin over the exit site.<ref name="Shored">{{cite journal|last1=Aguilar|first1=JC|title=Shored gunshot wound of exit. A phenomenon with identity crisis.|journal=Am J Forensic Med Pathol.|date=September 1983 |volume=4|issue=3|pages=199–204|pmid=6637946}}</ref>

The bullet shape influences the size of the abrasion collar.<ref name="Shape">{{cite journal|last1=Pircher|first1=R|last2=Pollak|first2=S|last3=Preiß|first3=D|last4=Thierauf-Emberger|first4=A|last5=Perdekamp|first5=MG|last6=Geisenberger|first6=D|title=The influence of the bullet shape on the width of abrasion collars and the size of gunshot entrance holes.|journal=Int J Legal Med|date=March 2017|volume=131|issue=2|pages=441–445|doi=10.1007/s00414-016-1501-6|pmid=27909866}}</ref> High velocity bullets with spitzer tip and [[full metal jacket bullet|full metal jacket]] are less likely to produce abrasion collar compared to civilian bullets which have a cylindrical round nose.<ref name="Thai">{{cite journal|last1=Peonim|first1=V|last2=Srisont|first2=S|last3=Udnoon|first3=J|last4=Wongwichai|first4=S|last5=Thapon|first5=A|last6=Worasuwannarak|first6=W|title=Entrance and exit wounds of high velocity bullet: An autopsy analysis in the event of dispersing the mass rally in Bangkok Thailand, May 2010.|journal=Leg Med (Tokyo).|date=November 2016|volume=23|pages=10–16|doi=10.1016/j.legalmed.2016.08.010|pmid=27890096|url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1344-6223(16)30084-0|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>

