{{Infobox cell | Name = Gonadotropic cell | Latin = | Image = | Caption = | Image2 = | Caption2 = | Precursor = | System = [[Reproductive system]] | Location = [[Anterior pituitary]] gland | Function = [[Gonadotropin]] secretion ([[follicle-stimulating hormone]] (FSH) and [[luteinizing hormone]] (LH)) }} '''Gonadotropic cells''' are [[endocrine]] [[cell (biology)|cells]] in the [[anterior pituitary]] that produce the [[gonadotropins]], such as the [[follicle-stimulating hormone]] (FSH) and [[luteinizing hormone]] (LH). Release of FSH and LH by gonadotropes is regulated by [[gonadotropin-releasing hormone]] (GnRH) from the [[hypothalamus]].<ref>Ganong, William F.: "Review of Medical Physiology", page 248. Lange, 2005.</ref>
Gonadotropes appear [[basophilic]] in histological preparations.
Gonadotropes have insulin receptors, which can be overstimulated by too high insulin levels. This may lead to infertility as hormone release levels are disrupted.<ref name=Brot2010>{{Cite journal | last1 = Brothers | first1 = K. J. | last2 = Wu | first2 = S. | last3 = Divall | first3 = S. A. | last4 = Messmer | first4 = M. R. | last5 = Kahn | first5 = C. R. | last6 = Miller | first6 = R. S. | last7 = Radovick | first7 = S. | last8 = Wondisford | first8 = F. E. | last9 = Wolfe | first9 = A. | doi = 10.1016/j.cmet.2010.06.010 | title = Rescue of Obesity-Induced Infertility in Female Mice due to a Pituitary-Specific Knockout of the Insulin Receptor (IR) | journal = Cell Metabolism | volume = 12 | issue = 3 | pages = 295–305 | year = 2010 | pmid = 20816095| pmc =2935812 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |vauthors=Hill JW, Elias CF, Fukuda M, Williams KW, Berglund ED, Holland WL, Cho YR, Chuang JC, Xu Y, Choi M, Lauzon D, Lee CE, Coppari R, Richardson JA, Zigman JM, Chua S, Scherer PE, Lowell BB, Brüning JC, Elmquist JK | title = Direct insulin and leptin action on pro-opiomelanocortin neurons is required for normal glucose homeostasis and fertility. | journal = Cell Metabolism | volume = 11| issue = 4| pages = 286–97| year = 2010 | pmid = 20374961| pmc = 2854520| doi = 10.1016/j.cmet.2010.03.002}}</ref>
Gonadotropes are feedback inhibited by specific hormones, including estradiol.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Estradiol-17beta inhibits gonadotropin-releasing hormone-induced Ca2+ in gonadotropes to regulate negative feedback on luteinizing hormone release|journal = Endocrinology|date = 2009-09-01|issn = 1945-7170|pmid = 19477939|pages = 4213–4220|volume = 150|issue = 9|doi = 10.1210/en.2009-0092|first = Javed|last = Iqbal|first2 = Olivier|last2 = Latchoumanin|first3 = Ika P.|last3 = Sari|first4 = Richard J.|last4 = Lang|first5 = Harold A.|last5 = Coleman|first6 = Helena C.|last6 = Parkington|first7 = Iain J.|last7 = Clarke}}</ref>
