[[File:Newborn Examination 1967.jpg||thumb|right|Examination of an infant]]
'''Lightwood's law''' is the principle that, in [[medicine]], [[bacterial]] infections will tend to localise while [[Virus|viral]] infections will tend to spread.<ref name="GillO'Brien2017">{{cite book|author1=Denis Gill|author2=Niall O'Brien|title=Paediatric Clinical Examination Made Easy|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GQVODgAAQBAJ&pg=PA246|date=9 March 2017|publisher=Elsevier Health Sciences|isbn=978-0-7020-7290-1|page=246}}</ref> This is based on the observation that while bacterial [[sepsis]] tends, despite affecting the whole body, to have a clear site of origin or 'focus', the opposite may be true of viral infections.<ref name="Stephenson2009">{{cite book|author=Terence Stephenson|title=Swine Flu: What Parents Need to Know|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=V1cSBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA48|year=2009|publisher=Jessica Kingsley Publishers|isbn=978-1-84905-085-2|page=48}}</ref> There may be multiple sites across the body which are affected including [[dermatological]] manifestations, [[respiratory]] symptoms and [[gastrointestinal]] symptoms. 

This principle is by no means infallible and in clinical practice a variety of diagnostic tests are used to distinguish between bacterial and viral infections.

