{{globalize|date=April 2015}}
'''Therapeutic Support Staff'''  - (TSS) are special education assistants within the commonwealth of [[Pennsylvania]]. They are trained to provide therapy to students with [[attention deficit hyperactivity disorder]], [[Tourette syndrome]], [[autism]], or other emotional support needs.

A TSS meets with a child in a one-on-one situation, with family, in public or at school to provide therapy. They work with the student to improve in areas such as social skills, behavioral rehabilitation, speech, motor skills, etc. TSS workers are often confused with a wrap around, which provide many of the same supportive therapies. A TSS worker has more in depth training and education on working with special needs, where a wraparound works mainly with children that have behavioral issues.

[[Category:Healthcare in Pennsylvania]]
[[Category:Mental health professionals]]


{{Mental-health-stub}}

The '''Vineland Social Maturity Scale''' is a psychometric assessment instrument designed to help in the assessment of social competence.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Tabitha Louis|first1=P|last2=Arnold Emerson|first2=I|title=Evaluating the cognition, behavior, and social profile of an adolescent with learning disabilities and assessing the effectiveness of an individualized educational program.|journal=Iranian Journal of Psychiatry and Behavioral Sciences|date=2013|volume=8|issue=2|pages=22–37|pmid=25053954|pmc=4105601}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gould|first1=J|title=The use of the Vineland Social Maturity Scale, the Merrill-Palmer Scale of mental tests (non-verbal items) and the Reynell Developmental Language Scales with children in contact with the services for severe mental retardation.|journal=Journal of mental deficiency research|date=September 1977|volume=21|issue=3|pages=213–26|pmid=144801}}</ref> It was developed by the American psychologist Edgar Arnold Doll.<ref name="Doll1953">{{cite book|last=Doll|first=Edgar Arnold|title=The measurement of social competence: a manual for the Vineland social maturity scale|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bRY8AAAAIAAJ|year=1953|publisher=Educational Test Bureau, Educational Publishers|doi=10.1037/11349-000}} archived at [https://archive.org/details/measurementofsoc1953doll]</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Doll|first1=E. A.|title=Annotated bibliography on the Vineland Social Maturity Scale.|journal=Journal of Consulting Psychology|date=1940|volume=4|issue=4|pages=123–132|doi=10.1037/h0063524}}</ref>

It is a quality [[Psychometrics|psychometric]] [[Psychological testing|questionnaire]] and a good measure of [[adaptive behavior]].<ref>Pedrini, D. T.; Pedrini, Bonnie C. [http://files.eric.ed.gov/fulltext/ED079342.pdf Vineland Social Maturity Scale Profile]</ref>

==Details==
The test consists of 8 sub-scales measuring:
* Communication skills
* General self-help ability
* Locomotion skills
* Occupation skills
* Self-direction
* Self-help eating
* Self-help dressing
* Socialization skills

