'''État second''' ([[French language|French]] for ''Second State'') refers to the state of mind into which some writers go when writing short stories. It mixes abstraction and concentration at the same time, ironically telling sometimes more facts than in conscious writing. The Argentine writer [[Julio Cortázar]] often used this method to write, as he called it "the moment of maximum creativity".<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://triangulaciones2850.blogspot.com/2006_07_01_archive.html |accessdate=2011-02-06 |title=CORTAZAR O LA ANTI-FRONTERA |date=2006-07-09 |last=Ron |first=Alex }}</ref>
==Cultural references== *The French version of the American movie ''[[Fearless (1993 film)|Fearless]]'' (1993) directed by [[Peter Weir]] was called ''État Second''.<ref>{{IMDb title|0106881}}</ref> *The Argentinian [[online magazine]] ''L´Etat Second mag''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coroflot.com/l-etatsecond|title=L´Etat Second|work=Coroflot|accessdate=25 March 2015}}</ref> also took its name from this term.
